Q:When would you want to use a remote repository rather than keeping all your work local?
A:When you work from another computer or dont have access to your local repository.

Q:Why might you want to always pull changes manually rather than having Git automatically stay up-to-date with your remote repository?
A:Because you decide when to make commit of single logic unit of work.

Q:Describe the differences between forks, clones, and branches. When would you use one instead of another?
A:You use fork when you want to clone someone github repo to your github.
You use clone when you want to get github repo to your local repo.
You use branch when you want make some changes that would not affect your
master branch.

Q:What is the benefit of having a copy of the last known state of the remote stored locally?
A:You can work with a last known state of the remote offline.

Q:How would you collaborate without using Git or GitHub? What would be easier, and what would be harder?
A:Git gives you all needed instruments for revision control of your local repo. And GitHub adds
opportunity to other people look at your project and suggest changes via pull requests.

Q:When would you want to make changes in a separate branch rather than directly in master? What benefits does each approach have?
A:When you add some features you not sure about, and want to get some collaboration from other
people, so you create pull requests.
